## IMPORTANT TERMS EXPLAINED SIMPLY

DEMAT ACCOUNT — Your digital locker where stocks are stored. Like a bank account but for shares. Zerodha, Upstox, Angel One are brokers who give you this.

PORTFOLIO — The collection of all stocks you currently own.

P&L — Profit and Loss. How much money you made or lost on your investments.

NIFTY 50 — Index of the 50 largest companies in India. The average temperature of the Indian stock market.

SENSEX — Same concept as Nifty but tracks 30 companies on BSE (Bombay Stock Exchange).

BULL MARKET — Market is going up. Investors are confident.

BEAR MARKET — Market is going down. Investors are fearful.

VOLATILITY — How wildly prices are swinging. High volatility means prices jumping dramatically.

PE RATIO — How expensive a stock is relative to its profits. PE of 10 means you pay ₹10 for every ₹1 the company earns. Lower PE generally means better value.

DIVIDEND — When a company shares profits with shareholders. If you own 100 shares and company declares ₹19 dividend — you get ₹1,900 in your account.

IPO (Initial Public Offering) — When a private company sells shares to the public for the first time.

SIP (Systematic Investment Plan) — Investing a fixed amount every month automatically.

MUTUAL FUND — Pool of money from many investors, managed by a professional who invests across many stocks.

DIVERSIFICATION — Not putting all eggs in one basket. Owning stocks from different sectors.

STOP LOSS — A pre-decided price at which you sell a stock to prevent further loss.

DRAWDOWN — How much your portfolio fell from its highest point.

CVaR (Conditional Value at Risk) — AEGIS's trigger mechanism. Looks at your portfolio's worst historical days and calculates your statistical worst-case loss threshold. If today's loss crosses that threshold — Recovery Engine activates.

SHARPE RATIO — Measures return per unit of risk. High Sharpe means good returns with low risk.

HEDGING — Taking a position that protects you if your main investment falls. Like buying gold ETF when worried about stocks falling.

FII (Foreign Institutional Investors) — Big foreign funds like American hedge funds and Middle Eastern sovereign wealth funds. They hold 20–22% of all Indian stocks. When they sell — markets fall. When they buy — markets rise.

DII (Domestic Institutional Investors) — Big Indian funds like LIC and SBI Mutual Fund. They counterbalance FIIs.

SGX NIFTY — Nifty 50 futures traded in Singapore overnight. Best predictor of how Indian markets will open at 9:15 AM.

SEBI — India's stock market regulator. Like RBI is for banks, SEBI is for stock markets.

REINFORCEMENT LEARNING — AI that learns by trial and error. Rewarded for good decisions, punished for bad ones. Trained on 20 years of market data.

LSTM — AI with built-in memory. Looks at 60 days of price data and predicts where price is heading next.

FINBERT — AI model trained specifically on financial news. Correctly interprets financial language and outputs Bullish/Neutral/Bearish score.

SHAP — Detective tool for AI. When portfolio drops, SHAP assigns blame percentages to each factor — showing exactly what caused the loss.

MONTE CARLO SIMULATION — Instead of predicting one future, runs 500 simulated futures based on historical precedent. Like a weather forecast — gives probability, not false certainty.

HIDDEN MARKOV MODEL — Classifies the current market mood — Bull, Bear, or High Volatility. AEGIS adjusts advice based on which mood is detected.

MISTRAL-7B — Open-source language model that runs locally on your device. Converts complex math into plain English or Hindi. Your data never leaves your device.

KELLY CRITERION — Mathematical formula for how much money to put into each trade. Prevents over-betting and under-betting.

RSI (Relative Strength Index) — Number from 0-100 showing if a stock is overbought (above 70) or oversold (below 30).

GREY MARKET PREMIUM (GMP) — Before an IPO officially lists, shares trade informally. The premium shows expected listing gains.

STCG — Short Term Capital Gains. Profit from selling a stock held under 12 months. Tax rate: 20%.

LTCG — Long Term Capital Gains. Profit from selling a stock held over 12 months. Tax rate: 12.5% above ₹1,25,000.

TAX LOSS HARVESTING — Selling a losing stock before March 31st so the loss cancels out your gains and reduces your tax bill. AEGIS identifies these automatically.

STT (Securities Transaction Tax) — Small government tax on every stock trade. 0.1% on sell side.

DISPOSITION EFFECT — Human tendency to sell winning stocks too early and hold losing stocks too long. One of the most costly behavioral biases. AEGIS detects this in your real trade history.

CANDLESTICK CHART — Most common stock chart. Green candle means price went up that day. Red candle means price went down.

