## TOUGH JUDGE QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS

Q: What if AEGIS gives wrong advice and someone loses money?
A: AEGIS never gives advice — it gives information and suggestions with clearly stated reasoning. Every output carries a disclaimer. Final decision is always the user's. Same as how Bloomberg Terminal works — data and analysis, not instructions.

Q: How is this different from ChatGPT?
A: ChatGPT doesn't know your portfolio, buying price, tax situation, or live market data. It gives generic advice to generic people. AEGIS knows everything about your specific financial situation. The difference is Google Maps versus asking a stranger for directions.

Q: Is this SEBI compliant?
A: AEGIS is a data analytics and information platform, not a SEBI-registered investment advisor. Similar to how Screener.in or Tickertape provide financial data. Every output carries a disclaimer that it is for informational purposes only.

Q: What about data privacy?
A: AEGIS uses read-only API access — we can never place orders or move money. All data is encrypted. We never sell user data. Users can disconnect Demat anytime and all data is deleted immediately.

Q: Everyone using the same AI — won't they all get the same signals?
A: No. Every user's output is personalised based on their specific holdings, buying prices, risk tolerance, and goals. A student with ₹50,000 and a retiree with ₹50,00,000 get completely different signals from the same market event.

Q: Univest already exists. Why would anyone switch?
A: Univest is a human analyst tip service behind a ₹99/month paywall with zero recovery plan when things go wrong. AEGIS is free, AI-powered, and built around the feature Univest completely ignores — explaining losses mathematically and providing a recovery path. Univest's 5 million users prove our market exists. Our job is to serve them better.

Q: Will everyone be profitable using AEGIS?
A: No — and we are honest about that. Markets are not guaranteed. AEGIS does not promise returns. It promises the elimination of self-inflicted losses caused by panic and poor decisions — which for most retail investors is worth more than any stock tip.

